<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-03-23T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-03-23T10:00:00-05:00" n="222" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d222">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">724.3415/2967: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Bolivia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Feely</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">La
                                    Paz</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-03-23T11:00:00-04:00">March 23, 1933—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 11:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>23. There is every indication that the Bolivian Government will not
                            accept a suspension of hostilities, even on the basis of positions
                            actually held, unless and until a prior agreement has been made for the
                            settlement of the fundamental question.</p>
                        <pb facs="0383" n="295" xml:id="pg_295"/>
                        <p>Recent military successes and the acquiescence of Chile in the free
                            transit of arms via Arica have greatly strengthened Bolivian confidence
                            in a successful issue of the military campaign.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Feely</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>